{"title_page": "All Saints Primary School, Gresford", "text_new": "''All Saints primary school''', Gresford was built in the memory of Thomas Vowlier Short, Bishop of St Asaph in 1874. It is a grade II listed building.\n\n<br />\n\n== Establishment ==\n[[File:All Saints Primary School Doorway.jpg|thumb|The dedication to Thomas Vowlier Short above the school doorway]]\nAll Saints primary school was built in memory of Thomas Volwlier Short.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/4589352/4589356/17/|title=Opening of the New School Gresford|last=|first=|date=1874-10-17|website=The Wrexham Advertiser|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The inscription above the school door says: ''<nowiki/>'These  school buildings were erected by relatives in affectionate memory of Thomas Vowlier Short, Late Bishop of St Asaph.  An earnest promoter of education who died at the vicarage in this parish April 13 1872''<nowiki/>'. \n<br />\n\n\n== Thomas Vowlier Short ==\n{{Main|Thomas Vowler Short}}Thomas Vowlier Short was the [[Bishop of St Asaph]] between 1864 and his retirement in 1870.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3306849/3306852/37/|title=The death of the late Bishop of St Asaph|last=|first=|date=1872-04-20|website=The Cambrian News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> He was a [[Theology|theologian]] who taught at [[Christ Church, Oxford|Christ Church]], University of Oxford, where he knew some of those later involved in the [[Oxford Movement]]. For Instance, [[Edward Bouverie Pusey|Edward Pusey]], was his favourite pupil, he examined [[John Henry Newman]], and was a friend of [[John Keble]]. <ref>{{Citation|last=Buckland|first=Augustus Robert|title=Short Thomas Vowler|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Short,_Thomas_Vowler_(DNB00)|work=Dictionary of National Biography, 1885-1900|volume=Volume 52|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>  On 13 April 1872, he died at the [[Gresford]] Vicarage, the home of Archdeacon Wickham, his brother-in-law.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n\n== Building ==\n[[File:All Saints' School, Gresford - geograph.org.uk - 1691965.jpg|thumb|All Saints Primary School]]\nThe building cost \u00a32,000,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.coflein.gov.uk/en/site/405290/details/all-saints-primary-school-school-hill-gresford|title=ALL SAINTS' PRIMARY SCHOOL, SCHOOL HILL, GRESFORD {{!}} Coflein|website=www.coflein.gov.uk|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> ,and was  built on a field purchased from the Chapter of Winchester. It was designed to accommodate 120 boys.  When it was opened it was described as being comprised of a master<nowiki>'s house and a schoolroom.  The schoolroom measured 52' 6'' by 18'</nowiki>. The exterior stone was from the [[Moss Valley, Wrexham|Moss valley]] quarries. It also incorporated ornamental bricks and plain varnished woodwork. The architect was Edward Jones, the diocesan surveyor. The building contractor was Benjamin Owen of Chester. On Monday 12 October 1874, the school was opened by the Bishop of St Asaph. He made a speech about the school's architecture and his predecessor.<ref name=\":0\" /> On 3 June 1996, the building became Grade II listed as an example of [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic revival style architecture]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n<br /> \n\n\n== Contemporary use ==\nThe original schoolroom forms part of the All Saints' Voluntary Aided Church in Wales School but the school master's house is a private dwelling. <ref name=\":2\" />\n\n\n<br />\n== References ==\n<references />\n[[Category:Grade II listed buildings in Wrexham County Borough]]\n[[Category:History of Wrexham County Borough]]\n[[Category:Wrexham]]\n", "text_old": "''All Saints primary school''', Gresford was built in the memory of Thomas Vowlier Short, Bishop of St Asaph in 1874. It is a grade II listed building.\n\n<br />\n\n== Establishment ==\n[[File:All Saints Primary School Doorway.jpg|thumb|The dedication to Thomas Vowlier Short above the school doorway]]\nAll Saints primary school was built in memory of Thomas Volwlier Short.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/4589352/4589356/17/|title=Opening of the New School Gresford|last=|first=|date=1874-10-17|website=The Wrexham Advertiser|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The inscription above the school door says: ''<nowiki/>'These  school buildings were erected by relatives in affectionate memory of Thomas Vowlier Short, Late Bishop of St Asaph.  An earnest promoter of education who died at the vicarage in this parish April 13 1872''<nowiki/>'. \n<br />\n\n\n== Thomas Vowlier Short ==\n{{Main|Thomas Vowler Short}}Thomas Vowlier Short was the [[Bishop of St Asaph]] between 1864 and his retirement in 1870.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/4589352/4589356/17/|title=The death of the late Bishop of St Asaph|last=|first=|date=1872-04-20|website=Wrexham Advertiser|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> He was a [[Theology|theologian]] who taught at [[Christ Church, Oxford|Christ Church]], University of Oxford, where he knew some of those later involved in the [[Oxford Movement]]. For Instance, [[Edward Bouverie Pusey|Edward Pusey]], was his favourite pupil, he examined [[John Henry Newman]], and was a friend of [[John Keble]]. <ref>{{Citation|last=Buckland|first=Augustus Robert|title=Short Thomas Vowler|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Short,_Thomas_Vowler_(DNB00)|work=Dictionary of National Biography, 1885-1900|volume=Volume 52|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>  On 13 April 1872, he died at the [[Gresford]] Vicarage, the home of his brother-in-law.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n\n== Building ==\n[[File:All Saints' School, Gresford - geograph.org.uk - 1691965.jpg|thumb|All Saints Primary School]]\nThe building cost \u00a32,000,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.coflein.gov.uk/en/site/405290/details/all-saints-primary-school-school-hill-gresford|title=ALL SAINTS' PRIMARY SCHOOL, SCHOOL HILL, GRESFORD {{!}} Coflein|website=www.coflein.gov.uk|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> ,and was  built on a field purchased from the Chapter of Winchester. It was designed to accommodate 120 boys.  When it was opened it was described as being comprised of a master<nowiki>'s house and a schoolroom.  The schoolroom measured 52' 6'' by 18'</nowiki>. The exterior stone was from the [[Moss Valley, Wrexham|Moss valley]] quarries. It also incorporated ornamental bricks and plain varnished woodwork. The architect was Edward Jones, the diocesan surveyor. The building contractor was Benjamin Owen of Chester. On Monday 12 October 1874, the school was opened by the Bishop of St Asaph. He made a speech about the school's architecture and his predecessor.<ref name=\":0\" /> On 3 June 1996, the building became Grade II listed as an example of [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic revival style architecture]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n<br /> \n\n\n== Contemporary use ==\nThe original schoolroom forms part of the All Saints' Voluntary Aided Church in Wales School but the school master's house is a private dwelling. <ref name=\":2\" />\n\n\n<br />\n== References ==\n<references />\n[[Category:Grade II listed buildings in Wrexham County Borough]]\n[[Category:History of Wrexham County Borough]]\n[[Category:Wrexham]]\n", "name_user": "WPCW", "label": "safe", "comment": "better reference", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/All_Saints_Primary_School,_Gresford"}
